WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hello everyone, this session covers the CS401 capstone project guidelines.

00:00:06.500 --> 00:00:13.000
The capstone represents 40% of your final grade and is due at the end of week 12.

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:20.000
You'll work in teams of two or three to build an end-to-end machine learning system.

00:00:20.500 --> 00:00:27.000
The project must include data collection or sourcing, preprocessing, model training, and evaluation.

00:00:27.500 --> 00:00:34.000
A short written report documenting your methodology and results is also required.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:41.000
Approved project domains include computer vision, natural language processing, and tabular prediction.

00:00:41.500 --> 00:00:48.000
You may also propose a custom domain — submit a one-paragraph pitch to me by end of week 3.

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:55.000
Your dataset must have at least 1000 labeled examples. Using an existing public dataset is fine.

00:00:55.500 --> 00:01:02.000
Kaggle, HuggingFace Datasets, and the UCI ML Repository are all acceptable sources.

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:09.000
If you collect your own data, you must include a data collection methodology section in your report.

00:01:09.500 --> 00:01:16.000
Baseline models must be included — you need something to compare your final model against.

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:23.000
A logistic regression or decision tree is sufficient as a baseline for most problems.

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:30.000
Your primary model should be a neural network of some form — this is a deep learning course.

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:37.000
You'll present your project in a 12-minute presentation during the final exam period.

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:44.000
The presentation should cover problem framing, data, model architecture, results, and learnings.

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:51.000
Grading rubric: 30% methodology, 30% results, 20% presentation quality, 20% written report.

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:58.000
All code must be submitted as a GitHub repository with a clear README and reproducibility instructions.

00:01:58.500 --> 00:02:05.000
Use virtual environments and pin your dependencies. We must be able to reproduce your results.

00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:12.000
Academic integrity policy: all work must be your own. Using pretrained models is allowed with attribution.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:19.000
Using ChatGPT or similar tools to write code is permitted if you document and understand it.

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:26.000
You cannot submit AI-generated code you do not understand or cannot explain in the presentation.

00:02:26.500 --> 00:02:33.000
Milestones: team registration by week 2, dataset confirmed by week 4, checkpoint demo in week 8.

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:40.000
The week 8 checkpoint demo is ungraded but mandatory — it keeps teams on track.

00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:47.000
Office hours are Tuesday 2 to 4pm. My PhD students are also available Wednesday afternoons.

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:54.000
Strong projects from previous years are linked on the course portal — highly recommend reviewing them.

00:02:54.500 --> 00:03:01.000
Remember: the goal is not a perfect model but a rigorous, reproducible scientific process.

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:07.000
Good luck with your team formation. Let me know if you have any questions.
